  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Brisbane's electricity network is hidden in plain sight. The local distribution lines on suburban streets fade into the background of any Australian neighbourhood, and few buyers think about them. The high-voltage transmission corridors that carry power from generation sites into the city are a different matter. They cut through residential suburbs in defined corridors, with steel lattice towers, registered easements on title, and physical presence that is impossible to ignore. For sellers in inner-east Brisbane suburbs where these corridors run, the conversation about powerlines becomes part of the sale campaign whether the seller raises it or the buyer does.</p>

      <p>This article is a practical guide for Brisbane sellers whose property sits on, beside, or within view of transmission infrastructure or significant distribution powerlines. It covers the legal disclosure that runs through the title, the buyer questions that come up at every inspection, the pricing reality for genuinely affected properties, and the conversation strategies that work when the infrastructure is part of the address.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Distribution lines, transmission lines, and the difference at sale</h2>
      <p>Not all powerlines are equal in a sale campaign. The standard timber-pole distribution lines that run along most Brisbane suburban streets carry low to medium voltage power from the local substation to individual houses. They are a normal part of the streetscape, no different from the streetlights or stormwater pits, and they almost never affect price. Buyers do not flag them, agents do not work around them, and selling near them needs no special preparation.</p>

      <p>High-voltage transmission lines are different. These are the lines carried on steel lattice towers, typically 66kV, 110kV, 132kV, 275kV, or above, operated by Powerlink Queensland for the bulk transmission network and by Energex for sub-transmission. They run in defined corridors with formal easements, the towers are large, the conductors visible, and the corridors are kept clear of significant vegetation and structures. Several inner-east and middle-ring Brisbane suburbs have transmission corridors passing through residential streets, and the properties directly affected by them are a recognisable category at sale.</p>

      <p>The seller's task at the start of any campaign is to be clear about which type of infrastructure affects the property. A title search will show any registered easement; a quick check of the property's surrounds will show any visible tower or overhead line. The framing of the campaign needs to match the reality: a small rooftop view of distant towers is a different conversation from an easement that crosses the back yard.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The easement on the title</h2>
      <p>If a transmission line crosses your property, there is almost certainly a registered easement on the title in favour of the network operator (Powerlink or Energex). The easement is a binding legal instrument that gives the operator rights to maintain, replace, and access the infrastructure, and it imposes restrictions on what the property owner can do within the easement corridor.</p>

      <p>Typical restrictions include no permanent structures within the easement, no swimming pools, no large outbuildings, height limits on planted vegetation, restrictions on tree species, and obligations to allow access for maintenance. The easement document itself will set out the specific terms, and a buyer's solicitor will read it carefully when reviewing the contract.</p>

      <p>For the seller, the steps are straightforward. Order a title search and obtain a copy of the registered easement document well before listing. Read it. Note the corridor width, the specific restrictions, any past correspondence with Powerlink or Energex about vegetation or access, and whether there are any improvements on the property that may be in conflict with the easement (a shed encroaching, a tree on the prohibited list, a pool installed outside the corridor that buyers might not realise is geometrically restricted from elsewhere on the lot). Brief your solicitor and your agent so the disclosure conversation is consistent across the campaign.</p>

      <p>For broader context on easements at sale, see our notes on <a href="/insights/easements-encumbrances-brisbane-property-sale" style="color:#f5d07a;">easements and encumbrances in a Brisbane property sale</a> and <a href="/insights/easements-property-brisbane-qld" style="color:#f5d07a;">easements on Queensland property titles</a>.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer questions you will be asked</h2>
      <p>Brisbane buyers inspecting a property near transmission infrastructure ask a predictable set of questions. Sellers and agents who prepare for them answer cleanly; those who do not stumble in front of the buyer and lose ground in the negotiation. The common questions are these.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Is there an easement on the title?</strong> The honest answer is yes or no, with the easement document available for the buyer's solicitor. Sellers who try to soften the answer ("I think there might be something") read as evasive. A confident, factual response reassures buyers that the seller has done the homework.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">What can and cannot be built on the affected part of the lot?</strong> The easement document gives the answer. Buyers planning a future extension or pool need to know specifically. The seller and agent should be able to point to the corridor on a site plan and describe the restrictions in plain language.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">What about electromagnetic fields and health concerns?</strong> This is the question many sellers fear. The honest answer is that public health agencies in Australia and internationally have studied the question for decades and have not concluded that residential exposure at typical distances from transmission lines causes adverse health outcomes. The regulatory framework that governs Australian transmission infrastructure includes exposure standards. The seller's job is not to advocate or downplay; it is to point to the published guidance and let the buyer make their own assessment. Pretending the question is unfair, or dismissing it, both backfire.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is the noise like?</strong> High-voltage lines can produce a faint hum, particularly in damp weather, which some buyers notice and others do not. The honest answer is to describe what the daily experience is like for the current household. If you have lived with it and it has not been an issue, say so. If it is occasionally noticeable, say that too.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Has there been any maintenance disruption?</strong> Powerlink and Energex carry out scheduled maintenance and occasionally vegetation work in transmission corridors. Buyers want to know what that has looked like in practice. A factual answer ("the operator accessed the easement once in the past five years for tree work, organised by them, with no disruption to the household") is far more useful than a vague reassurance.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The pricing reality</h2>
      <p>Sellers near transmission infrastructure sometimes hope a strong campaign and good presentation will eliminate the price effect of the lines. Sometimes that is true; usually it is partly true. The honest framing is that high-voltage transmission infrastructure does affect price for directly affected properties, but the size of the effect varies with several specific factors.</p>

      <p>The factors that increase the price effect are: the easement crossing the title rather than running adjacent; visibility of towers from the main living spaces and outdoor areas; the easement consuming a meaningful fraction of usable land; restrictions that prevent a future extension or pool that comparable properties could accommodate; and the lines being part of the dominant view rather than a peripheral one. The factors that reduce the price effect are: distance from the corridor of fifty metres or more; vegetation or topography that screens the towers from the home; the easement only clipping a corner of the lot; restrictions that do not affect the realistic use of the property; and a price guide that is set with the infrastructure already factored in rather than discovered mid-campaign.</p>

      <p>The pricing approach that works is to bring an experienced agent into the assessment early, look at recent sales of comparable properties affected and unaffected by the same corridor, and set a price guide that absorbs the realistic effect rather than testing the market. Properties that are priced at unaffected comparable levels and discovered to be affected mid-campaign almost always end up at a worse final number than properties priced honestly from the start.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing the property without overcompensating</h2>
      <p>The strongest campaigns for affected properties do not try to hide the infrastructure. They market the property's genuine strengths (location, layout, condition, character, school catchment) and let the affected area sit accurately within the listing. Photography that crops out the towers when they are part of the view is a short-term win; the buyer arrives at the inspection, sees the reality, and the credibility of the entire listing is reduced.</p>

      <p>The opposite approach also fails. Listings that lead with the infrastructure ("ideal for a buyer who can look past the lines") create a frame the buyer cannot escape. The right balance is to photograph the property honestly, including views that include the infrastructure when it is part of the property's reality, but to lead with what is genuinely strong. The buyer sees the truth without it being the headline.</p>

      <p>For inspection logistics, scheduling open homes at times when the lines are least visible (lower sun angles, when vegetation is in leaf rather than bare) is reasonable preparation, but it should not cross into deception. Buyers who attend a second inspection in different conditions will form their own complete view of the property, and any sense that the seller managed the first inspection to obscure something will undermine trust.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A practical pre-listing checklist</h2>
      <p>1. Order a current title search and obtain copies of any registered easements. 2. Identify the operator (Powerlink, Energex) and confirm the line voltage if possible. 3. Read the easement carefully, with your solicitor, and list the specific restrictions on the affected area. 4. Identify any improvements on the property that may interact with the easement (sheds, plantings, pool, fences). 5. Walk the property with your agent and decide which photographic angles are honest and which are misleading. 6. Prepare a one-page disclosure summary covering the easement, the restrictions, the operator's contact route, and any relevant history (maintenance, vegetation work, correspondence). 7. Brief your agent on the answers to the predictable buyer questions. 8. Set a price guide that incorporates the realistic effect, after looking at recent comparables. 9. Plan inspection logistics that present the property fairly without crossing into deception. 10. Have the easement document, title search, and disclosure summary ready for the buyer's solicitor on day one of the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The bottom line</h2>
      <p>Brisbane properties near transmission infrastructure are sold every week, and the sellers who handle the conversation well do not pretend the infrastructure is not there. They disclose the easement cleanly, prepare for the buyer questions, price the property realistically, and let the genuine strengths of the home carry the campaign. The cost of trying to hide or downplay the infrastructure is almost always higher than the cost of acknowledging it. Buyers who feel informed make decisions; buyers who feel managed walk away. For sellers in affected pockets of inner-east Brisbane, the right approach is the same one that works for any property with a clear feature requiring disclosure: be early, be specific, be confident, and let the buyer do the rest.</p>

